<h1 id="intro">Intro</h1><p>VHDL is a <strong>hardware modeling language, </strong>and not a programming language. An important part of programming languages is <strong>sequential</strong> steps, whereas hardware does a lot of things <strong>concurrently </strong>(a change to input <span class="ql-formula" data-value="x">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.43056em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span class="mord mathdefault">x</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span> may trigger many other changes at the same time).</p><p><br></p><p>Why do we use it?</p><ul><li><strong>Specification</strong> of design</li><li><strong>Simulation</strong> of design</li><li><strong>Synthesis</strong> of design (automatic generation of chip)</li></ul><p><br></p><p>VHDL can be used in many stages of hardware design:</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/QTaVixp.png" width="468"></p><p><br></p><p>What can we describe?</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/vkE9Qpr.png" width="350"></p><p><br></p><h1 id="terminology">Terminology</h1><ul><li><strong>Entity:</strong> your design</li><li><strong>Port(s): </strong>inputs and outputs</li><li><strong>Architecture: </strong>the function to be executed</li><li class="ql-indent-1"><strong>Behavioral: </strong>functional, such as <span class="ql-formula" data-value="a\ +\ b">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mtext>&nbsp;</mtext><mo>+</mo><mtext>&nbsp;</mtext><mi>b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">a\ +\ b</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.66666em; vertical-align: -0.08333em;"></span><span class="mord mathdefault">a</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2222222222222222em;"></span><span class="mspace">&nbsp;</span><span class="mbin">+</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2222222222222222em;"></span><span class="mspace">&nbsp;</span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.69444em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span class="mord mathdefault">b</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span> </li><li class="ql-indent-1"><strong>Structural: </strong>with components</li><li><strong>Signals: </strong>connections, and their <strong>values</strong></li><li class="ql-indent-1"><strong>Event(s): </strong>changes over time</li><li class="ql-indent-1"><strong>Propagation delays</strong></li><li class="ql-indent-1"><strong>Concurrency</strong></li><li class="ql-indent-1"><strong>Waveform:</strong> order series of events in time</li></ul><p><br></p><h1 id="concepts">Concepts</h1><h2 id="entity">Entity</h2><p>In an entity we define:</p><ul><li>The name of our design</li><li>The interface, a collection of <strong>ports:</strong></li><li class="ql-indent-1">Port usage: <strong>signals</strong></li><li class="ql-indent-1">Ports have a type, e.g. bit</li><li class="ql-indent-1">Ports have a mode: <em>in, out, inout</em></li></ul><p><br></p><p>The syntax looks as follows:</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/PviZV9f.png" width="428"></p><p><br></p><p>A more complex example:</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/j0elEQe.png" width="350"></p><p><br></p><p>As you can see for <span class="ql-formula" data-value="a,b,sum">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo separator="true">,</mo><mi>b</mi><mo separator="true">,</mo><mi>s</mi><mi>u</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">a,b,sum</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.8888799999999999em; vertical-align: -0.19444em;"></span><span class="mord mathdefault">a</span><span class="mpunct">,</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.16666666666666666em;"></span><span class="mord mathdefault">b</span><span class="mpunct">,</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.16666666666666666em;"></span><span class="mord mathdefault">s</span><span class="mord mathdefault">u</span><span class="mord mathdefault">m</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span>, a bit vector is used to specify that we want to use multiple bits as in/output. When specifying a bit vector, we need to specify its length using indices.</p><p><br></p><p>We can refer to a bit in this bit vector using <span class="ql-formula" data-value="a\left(5\right)">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mrow><mo fence="true">(</mo><mn>5</mn><mo fence="true">)</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">a\left(5\right)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;"></span><span class="mord mathdefault">a</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.16666666666666666em;"></span><span class="minner"><span class="mopen delimcenter" style="top: 0em;">(</span><span class="mord">5</span><span class="mclose delimcenter" style="top: 0em;">)</span></span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span> or <span class="ql-formula" data-value="a\left(5\ downto\ 2\right)">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mrow><mo fence="true">(</mo><mn>5</mn><mtext>&nbsp;</mtext><mi>d</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>w</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>t</mi><mi>o</mi><mtext>&nbsp;</mtext><mn>2</mn><mo fence="true">)</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">a\left(5\ downto\ 2\right)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;"></span><span class="mord mathdefault">a</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.16666666666666666em;"></span><span class="minner"><span class="mopen delimcenter" style="top: 0em;">(</span><span class="mord">5</span><span class="mspace">&nbsp;</span><span class="mord mathdefault">d</span><span class="mord mathdefault">o</span><span style="margin-right: 0.02691em;" class="mord mathdefault">w</span><span class="mord mathdefault">n</span><span class="mord mathdefault">t</span><span class="mord mathdefault">o</span><span class="mspace">&nbsp;</span><span class="mord">2</span><span class="mclose delimcenter" style="top: 0em;">)</span></span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span>.</p><p><br></p><h2 id="architecture">Architecture</h2><p>Each architecture is linked to an entity, entities can have multiple architectures. Each architecture must be given a name (in this case <em>my_half_adder_arch</em>) and must be linked to an entity using the <strong>of </strong>statement.</p><p><br></p><p>It consists of two parts:</p><ul><li><strong>Declarative region</strong>: instantiation of signals, components, etc</li><li><strong>Architecture body</strong>: real description of the functionality.&nbsp;</li></ul><p><br></p><p>Using simple signal assignment statements (done using <span class="ql-formula" data-value="<=">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mo>&amp;lt;</mo><mo>=</mo></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">&amp;lt;=</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.5782em; vertical-align: -0.0391em;"></span><span class="mrel">&lt;</span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.36687em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span class="mrel">=</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span>). Such a signal is a time-value pair, i.e. we have to specify a value and the time that this signal is assigned this value.</p><p><br></p><p>These signals are executed when <span class="ql-formula" data-value="a">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">a</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.43056em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span class="mord mathdefault">a</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span> or <span class="ql-formula" data-value="b">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mi>b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">b</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.69444em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span class="mord mathdefault">b</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span> changes, and the carry/sum change after <span class="ql-formula" data-value="5ns">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mn>5</mn><mi>n</mi><mi>s</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">5ns</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.64444em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span class="mord">5</span><span class="mord mathdefault">n</span><span class="mord mathdefault">s</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span>. You can swap the lines without any problems.</p><p><br></p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/Xzrdwwn.png" width="504"></p><p><br></p><h3 id="signals">Signals</h3><p>Using intermediate signals, longer expressions can be broken down without changing the functionality:</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/ZHgDXCK.png" width="430"></p><p><br></p><h3 id="pulse-width">Pulse width</h3><p>We can use the <strong>reject </strong><span class="ql-formula" data-value="x">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.43056em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span class="mord mathdefault">x</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span> <strong>ns </strong>statement in our signal expression to not execute our signal expression if the input changes back in <span class="ql-formula" data-value="x">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.43056em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span class="mord mathdefault">x</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span> ns.</p><p><br></p><h3 id="components">Components</h3><p>If you want to use an entity in another entity, make it into a <strong>component</strong>. Just copy-paste the entity code and replace entity by component.</p><p><br></p><h3 id="bits-vs-std_logic">Bits vs std_logic</h3><p>Bit type is standard in VHDL, but only has two values: ‘0’ and ‘1’. Usually more is needing in simulation, for which we can use <strong>std_logic </strong>(there is also <strong>std_ulogic, </strong>which stands for unresolved. This will be discussed later)<strong>:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>U</strong>: uninitialized, signal has not been set yet</li><li><strong>X</strong>: unknown, impossible to determine this value/result</li><li><strong>0:</strong> logical 0</li><li><strong>1:</strong> logical 1</li><li><strong>Z: </strong>high impedance</li><li><strong>W: </strong>weak signal, can't tell if it should be 0 or 1</li><li><strong>L: </strong>weak signal, probably 0</li><li><strong>H: </strong>weak signal, probably 1</li><li><strong>-: </strong>don't care</li></ul><p><br></p><p>We can also use <strong>std_logic_vector, </strong>similar to <strong>bit_vector.</strong></p><p><br></p><p>In order to use this we need to import it:</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/KCrCjsH.png" width="474"></p><h3 id=""><br></h3><h3 id="constant">Constant</h3><p>A constant can be defined as such:</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/0KUAXNV.png" width="563"></p><p><br></p><p>It can then be used everywhere in scope.</p><p><br></p><h3 id="conditional-signal-assignment">Conditional Signal Assignment</h3><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/VWTNn8W.png" width="542"></p><p>We need this last statement since we only used 4 of the <span class="ql-formula" data-value="2^8">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><msup><mn>2</mn><mn>8</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">2^8</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.8141079999999999em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span class="mord"><span class="mord">2</span><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.8141079999999999em;"><span class="" style="top: -3.063em; margin-right: 0.05em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 2.7em;"></span><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight">8</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span> options.</p><p><br></p><h3 id="configuration-specification">Configuration specification</h3><p>Since an entity can have several architecture descriptions, we need to be able to specify the one to use. This can be done using <strong>binding rules, </strong>which by default are the last compiled entity.</p><p><br></p><p>We can also specify this as follows:</p><p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="456"></p><p><br></p><p>This can be defined outside of the architecture as follows:</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/ES7FpfK.png" width="356"></p><p><br></p><h2 id="structural-vhdl">Structural VHDL</h2><p>Besides behavioral VHDL, there is also structural VHDL. The purpose of structural VHDL is to connect components together and several steps are needed to do this:</p><ul><li>Declare an entity as a component in the declarative region of an architecture</li><li>Give a name to one of the components via a label</li><li>State the component (name) that you want to use</li><li>Write “port map”</li><li>Use the port map list to connect the component port to either intermediate signals in the design of one of the port of the overall design</li><li>The symbol “=&gt;” is used to denote the port map</li><li>Left of the “=&gt;”-symbol is the component port name</li><li>Right of the “=&gt;”-symbol is the intermediate signal name of the input/output port name of the overall design </li></ul><p><br></p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/HRyYuAH.png" width="582"></p><p><br></p><p><strong>Example</strong></p><p>Another example of this is a full adder using two half adders and an OR gate (note that the two adders are the same, so we only needed to declare one component):</p><p><br></p><h3 id=""><img src="https://i.imgur.com/1IMwJse.png" width="525"></h3><p><br></p><h2 id="hierarchy-of-components">Hierarchy of components</h2><p>We can make an hierarchical tree of entities. The lowest level must have a functional description, the others can have a structural description.</p><p><br></p><h2 id="transport-delay-model">Transport delay model</h2><div style="white-space: normal;" class="markdown-body"><p><strong>Inertial delay:</strong> standard model, suitable for modelling delay of gates. Say we have <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>b</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><mtext>&nbsp;after&nbsp;</mtext><mn>20</mn><mi>n</mi><mi>s</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">b \lt= a \text{ after } 20 ns</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height:0.73354em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;"></span><span class="mord mathdefault">b</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;"></span><span class="mrel">&lt;</span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height:0.36687em;vertical-align:0em;"></span><span class="mrel">=</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;"></span><span class="mord mathdefault">a</span><span class="mord text"><span class="mord">&nbsp;after&nbsp;</span></span><span class="mord">2</span><span class="mord">0</span><span class="mord mathdefault">n</span><span class="mord mathdefault">s</span></span></span></span>, the value is assigned after 20ns of inertial delay. If <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">a</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;"></span><span class="mord mathdefault">a</span></span></span></span> changes back faster than 20ns, <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">b</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;"></span><span class="mord mathdefault">b</span></span></span></span> will remain unchanged.</p>

</div><p><br></p><p><strong>Delta delay:</strong> an infinitely small delay (still countable), to ensure the correct order of events</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/BoHBgfO.png" width="306"></p><p><br></p><h1 id="discrete-event-simulator">Discrete event simulator</h1><p>For simulating events, we know that:</p><ul><li><strong>Signal:</strong> time/value pair</li><li><strong>Event:</strong> changes in the value of signals at a certain time. Signal <span class="ql-formula" data-value="X">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.68333em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span style="margin-right: 0.07847em;" class="mord mathdefault">X</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span> gets new value <span class="ql-formula" data-value="Y">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.68333em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span style="margin-right: 0.22222em;" class="mord mathdefault">Y</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span> on time <span class="ql-formula" data-value="Z">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mi>Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">Z</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.68333em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span style="margin-right: 0.07153em;" class="mord mathdefault">Z</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span></li><li>We store all events in a list, order them by time. Simultaneous events are executed concurrently</li></ul><p><br></p><h2 id="simulation">Simulation</h2><p>Imagine we want to simulate the following circuit:</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/4b4T6Zm.png" width="419"></p><div style="white-space: normal;" class="markdown-body"><ol>
<li>We start with an initial list of events. In this case <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mtext>In1</mtext><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo separator="true">,</mo><mn>0</mn><mi>n</mi><mi>s</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">\text{In1} (1, 0ns)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;"></span><span class="mord text"><span class="mord">In1</span></span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord">1</span><span class="mpunct">,</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;"></span><span class="mord">0</span><span class="mord mathdefault">n</span><span class="mord mathdefault">s</span><span class="mclose">)</span></span></span></span> and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mtext>In2</mtext><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo separator="true">,</mo><mn>0</mn><mi>n</mi><mi>s</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">\text{In2} (1, 0ns)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;"></span><span class="mord text"><span class="mord">In2</span></span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord">1</span><span class="mpunct">,</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;"></span><span class="mord">0</span><span class="mord mathdefault">n</span><span class="mord mathdefault">s</span><span class="mclose">)</span></span></span></span>.</li>
<li>This yields new events: <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mtext>s1</mtext><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;"></span><span class="mord text"><span class="mord">s1</span></span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord">0</span><span class="mpunct">,</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;"></span><span class="mord">2</span><span class="mord mathdefault">n</span><span class="mord mathdefault">s</span><span class="mclose">)</span></span></span></span>, <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mtext>s2</mtext><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator="true">,</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi><mi>s</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">\text{s2} (0, 2ns)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;"></span><span class="mord text"><span class="mord">s2</span></span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord">0</span><span class="mpunct">,</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;"></span><span class="mord">2</span><span class="mord mathdefault">n</span><span class="mord mathdefault">s</span><span class="mclose">)</span></span></span></span>, <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mtext>s3</mtext><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo separator="true">,</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>n</mi><mi>s</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">\text{s3} (1, 5ns)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;"></span><span class="mord text"><span class="mord">s3</span></span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord">1</span><span class="mpunct">,</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;"></span><span class="mord">5</span><span class="mord mathdefault">n</span><span class="mord mathdefault">s</span><span class="mclose">)</span></span></span></span> and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mtext>s4</mtext><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo separator="true">,</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>n</mi><mi>s</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">\text{s4} (1, 5ns)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mpunct">,</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;"></span><span class="mord">5</span><span class="mord mathdefault">n</span><span class="mord mathdefault">s</span><span class="mclose">)</span></span></span></span>.</li>
<li>We then advance our time to the event on the top of our event list. Then we execute the events at this time, and add new events to this list.</li>
<li>In the end we end up with an empty event list, after which we stop.</li>
</ol>
</div><p><br></p><h1 id="process">Process</h1><p>A process is a list of signals. If any of the given signals experience a change, then the process is started.</p><p><br></p><p>Statements in a <strong>process</strong> are executed sequentially (from the beginning to the end), step by step.</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/IzZ8uKq.png" width="574"></p><p>Some notes:</p><ul><li>We can use some programming constructs (<strong>if, elseif</strong>), which also have a meaning in real hardware</li><li>We can use variables, which are independent of time, they only have a type. We can use variable assignment to assign values to this variable. The syntax can be seen in the previous image.</li><li>We can do <strong>sequential signal assignments</strong> within a process. If we do them "outside" of a process, i.e. outside of the process block, they are called <strong>concurrent signal assignments. </strong></li><li>The concurrent signal assignments can be executed independently from each other and even at the same time (concurrently)</li><li>A process requires 0 simulation time and it can schedule / generate events in the future</li></ul><p><br></p><p>Some programming constructs that we can use:</p><p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="523"></p><p>An example of how a half adder would look like:</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/PcJ7rHk.png" width="374"></p><p><br></p><h2 id="variables-vs-signals">Variables vs signals</h2><p>Given these two similar processes:</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/1ABLSaM.png" width="597"></p><p><br></p><p>The left process is executed sequentially, and its values update directly. So <strong>var_s1 </strong>and <strong>var_s2 </strong>don't have any delay. The only place where we have a little bit of delay is upon setting <strong>res1: </strong><span class="ql-formula" data-value="0ns+\Delta">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn><mi>n</mi><mi>s</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">Δ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">0ns+\Delta</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.72777em; vertical-align: -0.08333em;"></span><span class="mord">0</span><span class="mord mathdefault">n</span><span class="mord mathdefault">s</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2222222222222222em;"></span><span class="mbin">+</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2222222222222222em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.68333em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span class="mord">Δ</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span>. This is because of the <strong>"is" </strong>statement. The variables defined before is called the sensitivity list, and the process will rerun every time when a signal in this sensitivity list changes.</p><p><br></p><p>The right process is a bit more complicated, since there is a <span class="ql-formula" data-value="\Delta">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Δ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">\Delta</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.68333em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span class="mord">Δ</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span> delay every assignment. This means that in the second statement, we use the initial value of <strong>sig_s1 </strong>and not the updated value. The same goes for the third line, it is done at <span class="ql-formula" data-value="0ns+\Delta">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn><mi>n</mi><mi>s</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">Δ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">0ns+\Delta</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.72777em; vertical-align: -0.08333em;"></span><span class="mord">0</span><span class="mord mathdefault">n</span><span class="mord mathdefault">s</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2222222222222222em;"></span><span class="mbin">+</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2222222222222222em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.68333em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span class="mord">Δ</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span>.</p><p><br></p><h1 id="wait-statements">Wait statements</h1><p>We can wait on a few things:</p><ul><li><strong>wait for &lt;time expr&gt;</strong></li><li><strong>wait on &lt;signal&gt;</strong></li><li><strong>wait until &lt;boolean expr&gt;</strong></li></ul><p><br></p><p>This statement gives explicit control over suspending and resumption of a process. Multiple wait statements may be used in a process. </p><p><br></p><p>When waiting, progression of time can happen. Wait statements and sensitivity lists may never be used together:</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/9C6v6JV.png" width="397"></p><p>We can use them to make clocks:</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/4rP8fCC.png" width="451"></p><h1 id="generics">Generics</h1><p>We can pass parameters to components using generics:</p><ul><li>Generics are constant objects that can only be read</li><li>The value of generics must be known during compile-time</li><li>Generics are part of the entities interface, but don’t have a physical equivalent</li></ul><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/1OowYlz.png" width="362"></p><p><br></p><h1 id="modelling-of-state-machines">Modelling of state machines</h1><h2 id="meely-state-machine">Meely state machine</h2><p>You can see a Mealy state machine here (remember, its output depends on the state &amp; the input).</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/nFdZw6n.png" width="566"></p><p><br></p><h2 id="moore-state-machine">Moore state machine</h2><p>Note that the output <span class="ql-formula" data-value="z">﻿<span contenteditable="false"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math><semantics><mrow><mi>z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">z</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.43056em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span style="margin-right: 0.04398em;" class="mord mathdefault">z</span></span></span></span></span>﻿</span> only depends on the state.</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/5uBOpeZ.png" width="557"></p><p><br></p><h2 id="sync-/-async-reset">Sync / async reset</h2><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/iMaWaMf.png" width="442"></p><p>Note that in the sync reset, it changes the output on the rising edge of the clock.</p><p><br></p><p>In the async reset I need to pass the reset to the sensitivity list.</p><p><br></p><h1 id="attributes">Attributes</h1><div style="white-space: normal;" class="markdown-body"><p>Attributes are used to obtain information from VHDL "types", "arrays" and "signals". They are notated as <code>object'attribute</code>.</p>
</div><p><br></p><p>We have the following attribute types:</p><div style="white-space: normal;" class="markdown-body"><ul>
<li><strong>Value attributes</strong> (returns a constant value, e.g. <code>statetype'left</code>)</li>
<li><strong>Function attributes</strong> (invoke functions, e.g. <code>clk'event</code>)</li>
<li><strong>Signal attributes</strong> (creates a new signal, e.g. <code>signal_name'delayed(T)</code>)</li>
<li><strong>Type attributes</strong> (returns a type)</li>
<li><strong>Range attributes</strong> (returns a range, e.g. <code>value_range'range</code>)</li>
</ul>
</div><p><br></p><h1 id="functions">Functions</h1><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/R5mSUNG.png" width="455"></p><p>Some characteristics of functions:</p><ul><li>The parameters are: constants, signals and files. The mode is always <strong>in</strong></li><li>The default parameter is constant</li><li>Functions <strong>cannot change</strong> the (input) parameters</li><li>Function produce a <strong>single value</strong></li><li>When calling functions, the parameter types must match</li><li>Values of variables reinitialized at each call</li><li>Function may not contain wait statements nor signal assignments</li><li>Functions can call other functions</li></ul><p><br></p><p>The location of a function determines whether it is visible to its own process or to other processes, i.e. if we define it inside of a process, it will only be visible to that process.</p><p><br></p><p>An example function:</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/BJlPRqs.png" width="343"></p><p><br></p><h2 id="std_ulogic">std_ulogic</h2><p>It is possible for multiple drivers can be assigned to drive a single signal. In order to do this, we need some way to determine the actual value that becomes visible on the bus.</p><p><br></p><p>For that, we use resolution functions, which determine the actual output. The order of resolving the values must not determine the end result/value. This is why we have <strong>std_ulogic, </strong>which is a resolved version of the <strong>std_logic.</strong></p><p><br></p><p>These types have a resolution function built in:</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/et6WUTg.png" width="343"></p><p><br></p><h1 id="procedure">Procedure</h1><p>Procedure are more extensive versions of functions:</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/qZdS44a.png" width="475"></p><p><br></p><p>Some characteristics of procedures:</p><ul><li>The parameters are: variables, constants, signals, and files. The modes can be: <strong>in, out, inout</strong></li><li>Default type of parameters is: constant when mode <strong>in</strong>, otherwise variable</li><li>Values of variables reinitialized at each call</li><li>Procedures <strong>do not</strong> return values (as functions do)</li><li>Procedures can be called sequentially or concurrently and a concurrent procedure executes based on the <strong>in</strong> and <strong>inout</strong> parameters change</li><li>Procedures <strong>cannot contain</strong> wait statements when placed in a process that already has a sensitivity list and when used in a function</li><li>Procedures can also contain signal assignments on signals not specified in the parameter list... be careful</li></ul><p><br></p><p>An example procedure:</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/0Qv63LQ.png" width="434"></p><p>Since it is called outside of a process, it is a concurrent procedure call. Since the <strong>in </strong>and <strong>inout </strong>parameters of a concurrent procedure call act as a sensitivity list, changes of these signals will trigger the execution of a procedure.</p><p><br></p><p>If we call this procedure sequentially, we need to make sure the relevant signals are placed in the wait statements to ensure that this sequential procedure is executed in the exactly the same way as the previous concurrent procedure call, as it would otherwise keep calling the procedure.</p><p><br></p><h1 id="leftovers">Leftovers</h1><h2 id="subprogram-overloading">Subprogram overloading</h2><p>If you have a program, such as a flip flop, which comes in many forms, you'd have to define a name for each type. For this we have subprogram overloading, where all the different designs (procedures) can use the same name. When a procedure is used, the compiler will match the parameter list with the appropriate procedure based on the parameter list.</p><p><br></p><h2 id="packages">Packages</h2><p>We can combine functions, procedures, types, attributes, etc into a package. Only the declared content is visible for use.</p><p><br></p><p>You declare (so no definitions) your package as such:</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/0WlyjMI.png" width="269"></p><p><br></p><p>In the body you actually put the definitions. This body is usually in the same file as the package declaration.</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/mFLFJZw.png" width="410"></p><p><br></p><h3 id="libraries">Libraries</h3><p>You can put packages together in libraries. The libraries STD and WORK are implicitly defined.</p><p><br></p><h3 id="imports">Imports</h3><p>You can import a library using:</p><p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/Nn2KRI9.png" width="298"></p><p>This import only applies to the first entity in your code, so you need to repeat this import!</p><p><br></p><h3 id="simulation-vs-synthesis">Simulation vs synthesis</h3><ul><li><strong>Simulation:</strong> determine function of VHDL model</li><li><strong>Synthesis:</strong> generate hardware from VHDL model</li></ul>
